I kind of liked the old version that had most of the actual dates for Icehouse (in contrast to the planned ones). Then again, maybe that was already information overload for a slide image.

The column used by the old (Icehouse) version to mention release version and date (curiously called "Swift"!?) is now entirely empty and might as well be removed.

Also puzzling: looking at the repo, it is not clear to me where the source file for this image is stored.

Long story short, this image needs updating at some point in the future, but a) for this changeset, I abstain until those who actually use the slides have weighed in, and b) I suspect the image needs an additional, more radical update.'}, {'account_id': 7007, 'date': '2015-01-21 11:17:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

I agree with Roger, this image may need more radicle changes in future. It is a bit confusing for me to go through this image. It requires me to do some guess work to understand this image.'}, {'account_id': 11889, 'date': '2015-01-21 13:18:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

@Roger: "Swift" column is for Swift versions. see https://github.com/openstack/swift/releases

This is a screenshot of the wiki table at https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Kilo_Release_Schedule. I'm also not sure how much value is added by the last Swift column at all, but I guess it's not worth the hassle of manually changing this with every release. 

Also, Swift has a bit different release schedule, so if you look at the Release schedule wiki page, they explicitly mention that in the "Important notes". 

So until the wiki page is updated with released versions of Swift (like in older release schedules), maybe we shouldn't merge this? Thierry updates wiki page later in the development cycle (look at the wiki page history). Until then, it's less confusing to use older Release schedule.'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2015-01-21 13:27:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Thank you so much for the explanation, Matjaz.'}, {'account_id': 6923, 'date': '2015-02-23 18:57:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

So Kato, update the patch with an bit on what the schedule is and a bit on swift release schedule.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-31 00:05:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 10497, 'date': '2015-05-16 05:47:41.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

nova.conf config flags were not properly implemented in t he correct
containers.

This patch moves the nova.conf config flags for vnc to the proper
containers. Additionally, the patch modifies the proxy client ip

commit_message:
Fixes Nova NoVNC

Previously, vnc was not completely working properly because
nova.conf config flags were not properly implemented in t he correct
containers.

This patch moves the nova.conf config flags for vnc to the proper
containers. Additionally, the patch modifies the proxy client ip
param to be consistent with the param within nova.conf and adds
all the novnc params to docs.

Change-Id: I1944baca64ccd113bbca582784b08f90dc0eff69
(cherry picked from commit fa51eb4b5377e4725c0438fbfe85cdacdab8b3fe)

commit_message:
Fix the klwt link

The lp link of klwt spec is wrong now, this change fixes it.
Although this is minor fix, but it will be valuable if we want to know
the change details from the spec Wiki page.

Change-Id: Ia479acf15fac70a36de2419837475383c31a8186

subject: cinder setup now refers to CINDER_VOLUME_CLEAR and volume_clear

commit_message:
cinder setup now refers to CINDER_VOLUME_CLEAR and volume_clear

CINDER_SECURE_DELETE previously iniset volume_clear to none as a
side effect, however secure_delete is not documented in cinder.
Now using CINDER_VOLUME_CLEAR outright. CINDER_SECURE_DELETE is
supported but now deprecated.

Change-Id: Ic8694cf16654c23b27d23853a9f06ddf1050fa93
Closes-Bug: #1450159

commit_message:
Moved the playbook vars to defaults

This change will make it so that the specific versions of OpenStack
package sources can be overridden using hostvars and or a
user_variable. This should assist in the developer case where various
versions of things may be desirable.

Change-Id: I30d84ee6840f224a7687179c522e6e9c38ec58a4
(cherry picked from commit 3e7666373a231d8fad1e67c9dc27025b3d9de9f6)

commit_message:
Start the conversion to oslo.versionedobjects

This is a first commit to make a mostly trivial step towards using
oslo.versionedobjects in Nova. It substitutes our dict compat class
for the one in the library, and officially makes the library a
requirement.

Related to blueprint use-oslo-objects

Change-Id: Ie23108123ac774b421a050c3aa5d1c29b27d6eb3

[{'created': '2015-05-15 23:56:09.000000000', 'message': 'Remove session.construct

This was a horrible interface that was designed to allow all these
variables to be passes to a client object and session to take what it
needed. We no longer want to recommend this method so remove the
function.

Change-Id: I2337c395b343bfd607ae62ecf6542dfea678f390
'}]
commit_message:
Remove session.construct

This was a horrible interface that was designed to allow all these
variables to be passes to a client object and session to take what it
needed. We no longer want to recommend this method so remove the
function.

Change-Id: I2337c395b343bfd607ae62ecf6542dfea678f390

commit_message:
Move catalog hack functions to keystoneauth

The get_catalog_discover_hack function was public within keystoneclient
because the module was private. Now that the module is public the
function should be private.

Add the existing public function add_catalog_discover_hack to
keystoneauth.

Change-Id: If71b660acf7c0d043a8e536555b346f164617a24

I see where you're going with this, and this patch will stop the automatic deletion of instances in active/passive failover.

However, active/passive failover will still be badly, badly broken in myriad other ways, because instance.host will not correspond to compute.manager.host on the Nova it's running on.

Rather than doing this, I would focus on some other way to prevent Nova from coming up in the first place. Until this is addressed fully this is only going to result in pain for any misguided user who tries to do this.

Incidentally, I suspect that if a user configured active/passive with failover ip/dns and host set to the same value on both, this would work fine.

I suspect != QA ;)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-09 16:09:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

I outlined the problems with this approach a little more fully here:

http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-February/056619.html

This patch only addresses one symptom of a much larger brokenness. Your system may appear to function with this in place, but only superficially.

I understand you also want to fix the underlying issue, which is great. However, if you do that, this patch isn't required any more, so I don't believe this has long term relevance. After all, the VMware driver might support evacuate some day. Supporting evacuate is actually orthogonal to this bug.

The expedient fix is to detect this situation and prevent it. I have proposed a way to do that, but I'd be open to other suggestions. My solution involves storing state on the hypervisor. If we could come up with a way that didn't require that, it would be applicable to all drivers. That would be better.

Also note that it appears HA could be configured if compute.manager.host is the same across all HA nodes. We just have to be careful they don't run simultaneously, as that would break some of our locking assumptions."}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-02-12 15:14:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

There are a number of issues at hand here:
1. ensuring that running instance are not deleted when a compute node starts. this is effectively what this patch does. that has catastrophic consequences.
2. what you suggest in the mail is a approach that i think is too tight and effectively prevent someone working in a HA mode (i have also not taken a look at the implementation details in detail)
3. as a community we need to try and address this issue. on IRC we chatted and you brought of the idea (which I like about the compute driver returning the host_id). That approach is more robust and can be leveraged by a VC driver. I think that we need to discuss that more at a forum like the summit.

This patch is just bandaid that will ensure that the running instances are not blown away.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-02-13 21:42:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

So, I actually think that we probably want a way to turn off evacuate for a variety of reasons. For one, there might be some driver-specific reason, as you have noted here. For another, the hypervisor may have changed hostnames. Or, someone may just think it's kinda nuts for the startup code in nova-compute to decide to delete all the instances under any circumstance :)

However, I don't think the semantic of "supports evacuate" is equivalent with "could end up with two services managing the same node", nor do I think that going forward we would want to rule that out in an HA situation.

What I'm getting at is, I don't think this is right as a capability, but I think a config value to disable the aggressive evacuate cleanup routine might be good.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2015-03-01 08:24:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-01 09:20:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Destroying evactuated instances at boot time may be problematic
for a number of reasons:
1. if the host name changes on a host all running instances on that
   host may be blown away if the host restarts
2. Not all drivers support destrthis functioanlity. For example the
   VMware driver does not have a 1:1 relationship between a
   compute node and the hypervisors. In this case starting a
   redundant backup nova compute will delete running instances.

A configuration variable destroy_evacuated_instances has been introduced
to enable an adminsitrator to disable this functionality if they wish.

This is enabled by default to support backwards compatability.

DocImpact

Closes-bug: #1419785

Change-Id: I4cfd4fa25228796ea67c6790bbe2d8d1f9ec3e0a
'}, {'created': '2015-03-05 10:55:02.000000000', 'message': 'Virt: add in supports_evacuate capabilities

VMware driver does not have a 1:1 relationship between a
compute node and the hypervisors. In this case starting a

Change-Id: I4cfd4fa25228796ea67c6790bbe2d8d1f9ec3e0a
'}]
commit_message:
Virt: add in supports_evacuate capabilities

Not all drivers support this functioanlity. For example the
VMware driver does not have a 1:1 relationship between a
compute node and the hypervisors. In this case starting a
redundant backup nova compute will delete running instances.

Closes-bug: #1419785

Change-Id: I4cfd4fa25228796ea67c6790bbe2d8d1f9ec3e0a

commit_message:
Remove XML middleware stub

As of last release (Kilo), Keystone removed XML support. A stub was left as a
way to communicate final deprecation to deployers. It was noted that this stub
would be removed in the Liberty release.

bp removed-as-of-liberty

Change-Id: I6e81e81451d02b4f39d00b2dc40947cfe3c3578b

commit_message:
Rework akanda-horizon packaging

This is a rework of the repository packaging to:

    * Renames project to akanda-horizon
    * Moves all code to akanda_horizon module
    * Updates setup.cfg/setup.py for PBR
    * Moves openstack extensions to a subdir

This updates setup.cfg/.py for pbr, renames the project to akanda-horizon
and moves dashboard extensions into a subdirectory.

Change-Id: I5cb1dad2e7dd7f47d0bac2ac39bdf34348fa6240

[{'created': '2015-05-13 17:23:33.000000000', 'message': "Fix race between resource audit and cpu pinning

This fixes a race between the claimed CPUs of an instance being
persisted to the DB, and the resource audit scanning the DB for
instances and subtracting pinned CPUs from the list of available CPUs.

The problem only shows up when the following sequence happens:
1) instance A (with dedicated cpus) boots on a compute node
2) resource audit runs on that compute node
3) instance B (with dedicated cpus) boots on the same compute node

The bug is that the claimed numa topology isn't updated until
after we release COMPUTE_RESOURCES_SEMAPHORE, so when the resource
audit retrieves the list of instances the numa_topology hasn't
been updated yet for the most recent one.

The fix is to persist the claimed numa topology at the same time
that we persist the instance host and node.  (And for the same
reason, that we want to be under COMPUTE_RESOURCES_SEMAPHORE
while doing it.)

Closes-Bug: #1454451
Change-Id: I553f2e43a68577c83d890c3671380af68f9e725a

commit_message:
Fix race between resource audit and cpu pinning

This fixes a race between the claimed CPUs of an instance being
persisted to the DB, and the resource audit scanning the DB for
instances and subtracting pinned CPUs from the list of available CPUs.

The problem only shows up when the following sequence happens:
1) instance A (with dedicated cpus) boots on a compute node
2) resource audit runs on that compute node
3) instance B (with dedicated cpus) boots on the same compute node

The bug is that the claimed numa topology isn't updated until
after we release COMPUTE_RESOURCES_SEMAPHORE, so when the resource
audit retrieves the list of instances the numa_topology hasn't
been updated yet for the most recent one.

The fix is to persist the claimed numa topology before releasing
COMPUTE_RESOURCES_SEMAPHORE.

Closes-Bug: #1454451
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I553f2e43a68577c83d890c3671380af68f9e725a

commit_message:
force the udp checksum for dhcp

The default vm setting assume udp checksums will be computed in
hardware. This fix forces the appliance to calculate the checksum for
DHCP replies.

This fix was inspired by the upstream reference implementation [1].

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/148718/8/neutron/agent/linux/dhcp.py

Change-Id: Id5d4ecdb3ce803b4b2a571f9033a637b7818ee08
(cherry picked from commit fc15f4b404267c4477710cdb1b3b65742a5124ad)

commit_message:
Seed a functional test suite with a basic health check

This creates a base functional test suite with a minimal health check
of the service VM.  We can fill this in with richer tests as we go, but
in the meantime this will give us something to at least test that devstack
deployments and image builds produce a reachable VM via its management
port.

Change-Id: I304718e8d3cb270b1ff3b5ad46a027facb42f2af
(cherry picked from commit bd28d7fb65882a1be04799ac5d46104cbc7a0892)

commit_message:
Add tools/run_functional.sh

Adds a place holder for what will be the entry point into the akanda
functional test suite.  devstack-gate will call this script via a
post_test_hook after it's spun up a devstack-backed cloud.  This is
a noop for now until the devstack-gate glue is in place and we have
something we can test.

Change-Id: Ieb25645801a32f1262ddb2967e834755f813892a
(cherry picked from commit c91547cbd63bfb186bdde4fc820606d62f46d80e)

commit_message:
Point DIB builds at the devstack checkout of akanda-appliance

This allows the built appliance image to contain the code that was
checked out by devstack, allowing people (or bots) to test
code that has not landed in the akanda-appliance repo.

Change-Id: I25c0278b6f3879a45bf52888b83eeb20d9571807
(cherry picked from commit 3ecf4fddb237f9aac43996a22621fb24a46222c4)

commit_message:
Fix dev quickstart, do not overwrite local.conf

The current docs show the examples overwritting config when setting
it to build an image, rather than appending to it.

Also, this adds a note about minimum memory requirements for the devstack
host machine.

Change-Id: Ie3199c2c90c43df99a4e1c4f01f5d9536bc8d5d9
(cherry picked from commit 89a8663e573d3e72e558b49d1cc7623607325c3e)

commit_message:
Get rid of circular references in Resource and Function

Circular references cause practically every bit of data that Heat uses to
remain in memory until the completion of an operation, and even then to
only be freed once the loop is detected by the garbage collector. By
breaking all of the loops using weak references, we can ensure that things
will get freed when they are no longer referenced without the need to wait
for garbage collection (which should also take a lot less time). This
change removes the loops from Resource and Function objects back to the
Stack.

Change-Id: Ibf80e95e69a2f27ed29754a2e0f1125e8eed0775
Closes-Bug: #1454873

commit_message:
Typo in openstack client help

The openstack client output for the help of --os-user-id states
"longin" instead of "login".  The openstack client gets it's help
output from the keystoneclient.

Change-Id: I7c92a82cd60b2835d98101200cf641b46dd145b4
Closes-Bug: #1455673

commit_message:
Eqlx: Fixes the retries on Network Connection Error

Volume creations were failing due to ssh connection
errors throwing ProcessExecutionError
and retries were not happening. Made a fix
to retry commands on both network errors and
backend api exceptions.
The parameter eqlx_cli_max_retries determines
the number of retry attempts made.

Closes Bug: #1441719
Change-Id: I54b76afc6c9c5d51dd9c38831ee0a1c731c7b161

commit_message:
Use self.configuration NOT CONF

The base driver initialize_connection method includes
a specific check for lioadm iscsi_helper.  This check
when True results in a call to lio initialize_connection.

The problem is not all backends need/use the iscsi_helper
conf settings, but if it's set, it will always evaluate
during the initialize_connection call and try to call the
drivers method, which in a number of cases won't exist.

This is particularly problematic as more customers are moving
to RHEL based Juno deployments which configure LIO as the default
iscsi_helper.

The fix for this is simple, just use self.configuration so that
the check is only for the instantiation of the driver being used.

There are a number of places in the base driver that maybe should
be switched from CONF to self.configuration, but changing all of
them is high risk for a backport to Juno.

NOTE:  There is no cherry pick to pull back for this change.  The
target code was rewritten in Kilo making this bug obsolete, but
also resulting in no change to backport.

Change-Id: Icc4ba8d0ae7ccdb88f8b5d68eec4625a91986af7
Closes-Bug: #1455249

commit_message:
Support short names for vdisks

There is a 15-character limit on virtual disk names, imposed by VIOS
(but not by the PowerVM REST API).  There is no such limit for SSP LUs.
The recently-changed disk name generation algorithm allowed vdisk names
to exceed 15 characters, causing errors like:

Failed to perform operation on Volume Group on VIOS with ID 2 in CEC
8247-22L*1234A0A - RMC command for Virtual Disk failed with error -

Backing device names can not exceed "15" characters in length.

This change set adds an optional 'short' parameter to the private
_get_disk_name helper which causes it to limit the generated name to 15
characters.  The localdisk driver is changed to use this new parameter.
Unit tests are improved such that they no longer mock _get_disk_name,
and such that they verify both of its variants.

Change-Id: I9efbb9d904e52f2a74bba7d8e631cd45862aa504

commit_message:
Fix share-server resources cleanup in generic driver

Generic driver using Neutron creates and attaches service subnets to router.
When we have more than one share server using same service subnet and delete
one of them, then Manila removes service subnet from router.
It is improper behaviour, because other, not deleted, share servers lose
connection in that case. So, add port validation to get to know for sure,
whether service subnet is used or not.

Change-Id: I6e7d4c1b40304be39f84a23c00433f47a295d02c
Closes-Bug: #1452747
(cherry picked from commit c7f57b0d7bf2c45d30f8494a5fb4b6d42ec38583)

commit_message:
Set local_ip only when TENANT_TUNNELS are enabled

In an installation with VLAN tenant networks, devstack should
not configure the local_ip (which is applicable only when
tenant_tunnels are used). This is causing failures in Neutron
for an IPv6 only setup. This patch addresses this issue, but
configuring the local_ip only when TENANT_TUNNELS are enabled.

Related-Bug: #1447693
Change-Id: I0e2a2d8b6ce0ad87f6c0d318ac522dbab50d44ee

commit_message:
VMware: Handle concurrent inventory folder create

Cinder volumes are organized under vCenter inventory folder
with name given by config option vmware_volume_folder. During
volume creation, this folder is created only if it doesn't
exist. Concurrent volume create operations when there is no
such folder can result in a race condition-- some of the
create operations will fail due to already existing folder.
This patch fix this by ignoring the exception and returning a
reference to the existing folder.

Change-Id: Ic9371957bb76a032985363880fbebda523574305
Closes-Bug: #1436844

CLI.  Also added a unit test for update.

To enable a wider team (including those from the SDK effort) to have
a say in how keystoneauth is managed as a library, add a dedicated
core group for both the library and release. This will allow for
keystoneauth to include cross-team core members without needing
to add these members to the core team that manages keystone server

commit_message:
Add keystoneauth-core group

To enable a wider team (including those from the SDK effort) to have
a say in how keystoneauth is managed as a library, add a dedicated
core group for both the library and release. This will allow for
keystoneauth to include cross-team core members without needing
to add these members to the core team that manages keystone server
code.

The plan is to also include the keystone-core and keystone-release
groups respectively.

Correct the help text for the compute option.

This patch describes the correct version cap for compute compat flag
during the live upgrade procedure.

commit_message:
Split instance event/tag correctly

External instance events are named with '-', while in the same time
it's combined with the tag using '-' to form a key. When splitting the
key to get event and tag, rsplit should be used

Change-Id: I13f1b40b8171a8a6ef77196aa6b6b68279fe57e4

[{'created': '2015-05-04 11:18:05.000000000', 'message': "VMWare: Isolate unit tests from requests

The test_ipv6_host_read actually tested all the way down to the
requests url call, which means it's testing a lot of function
unrelated to the nova code. The interesting part of this test seems to
be that it builds the ipv6 url correctly.

Change this into an assert based on that url being correct. Still keep
requests mocked out so we don't actually try to connect (though it's a
bit weird that __init__ calls create http connections magically).

Unblocks nova patches, which are failing on unit test since the latest
requests release and one of the function signatures changing.

Change-Id: I8ae4cb00e63cbb0304210dba2cd4993016d852ba
Closes-bug: #1451389
"}, {'created': '2015-05-04 11:43:07.000000000', 'message': "VMWare: Isolate unit tests from requests

requests url call, which means it's testing a lot of function
unrelated to the nova code. The interesting part of this test seems to
be that it builds the ipv6 url correctly.

Change this into an assert based on that url being correct. We still

Unblocks nova patches, which are failing on unit test since the latest

Change-Id: I8ae4cb00e63cbb0304210dba2cd4993016d852ba

commit_message:
VMWare: Isolate unit tests from requests

The test_ipv6_host_read actually tested all the way down to the
requests url call, which means it's testing a lot of function
unrelated to the nova code. The interesting part of this test seems to
be that it builds the ipv6 url correctly.

Change this into an assert based on that url being correct. We still
need to mock out the http connection because that's done magically in
__init__.

Unblocks nova patches, which are failing on unit test since the latest
requests release and one of the function signatures changing.

Change-Id: I8ae4cb00e63cbb0304210dba2cd4993016d852ba
Closes-bug: #1451389

commit_message:
Add datasource action API for action-execution-interface

The changes add additional API to execute an action on a specified
service, e.g. POST v1/data-sources/nova?action=execute
{'name': 'disconnect',
 'args': {'positional: ['vm123'],
          'named': {'key1': 'value1'}}

Implements: blueprint action-execution-interface

Change-Id: Ie220f4ea7739548e5f6d6855bc03c81ca4f818f4

commit_message:
Drop use of 'oslo' namespace package

The Oslo libraries have moved all of their code out of the 'oslo'
namespace package into per-library packages. The namespace package was
retained during kilo for backwards compatibility, but will be removed by
the liberty-2 milestone. This change removes the use of the namespace
package, replacing it with the new package names.

The patches in the libraries will be put on hold until application
patches have landed, or L2, whichever comes first. At that point, new
versions of the libraries without namespace packages will be released as
a major version update.

Please merge this patch, or an equivalent, before L2 to avoid problems
with those library releases.

Blueprint: remove-namespace-packages
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo-incubator/+spec/remove-namespace-packages

Change-Id: Id86b74fb492e1b86d29197b4e127d8368affa3fd

subject: Grammar change to implement modal-operators-2 BP
messages:
[{'account_id': 13644, 'date': '2015-04-16 17:32:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-16 17:52:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-congress-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/76/174476/1/check/gate-congress-pep8/037823c/ : SUCCESS in 2m 45s
- gate-congress-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/76/174476/1/check/gate-congress-python27/4918e8a/ : SUCCESS in 3m 06s
- gate-congress-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/76/174476/1/check/gate-congress-python34/61077bf/ : FAILURE in 43s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-04-17 14:45:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

Just a few suggestions.'}, {'account_id': 13644, 'date': '2015-04-20 01:29:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Line 74:     | COMMENT
Does COMMENT belong here?  Seems like a comment 
shouldn't be treated as a formula.

<jcs> I was scared to alter the overall structure, but now that this concern is gone, this is fixed. </jcs>

 Line 88:     ;
 Some of these names are a bit confusing b/c we have 2 layers of modals (the ones that apply to the rule as a whole and the ones that apply to individual atoms).  In particular, 'non_modal_rule' includes (atomic) modals, which is confusing b/c the other case here is to use 'modal'.  Can we come up with names that make this easier to understand (and feel free to change 'modal', etc. as well).

<jcs> Restructured the parser to take care of this problem. Replaced 'modal' with 'fact', which is more Datalog-ish and imho easier to understand (especially when the old modal did not have a modal entity). </jcs>


 Line 97:     ;
 Right now the second argument to insert/delete will be the name of the policy to insert/delete into.  (That's the other field in the Event class.)  There's no way currently to include the rule_name.   So maybe instead of 'rule_name', we could use 'policy_name'.

<jcs> Done </jcs>"}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-05-15 20:02:08.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Subsumed by another patch'}]

commit_message:
Moved the playbook vars to defaults

This change will make it so that the specific versions of OpenStack
package sources can be overridden using hostvars and or a
user_variable. This should assist in the developer case where various
versions of things may be desirable.

Change-Id: I30d84ee6840f224a7687179c522e6e9c38ec58a4

commit_message:
Sanitation of metadata passed from Django

We need to escape HTML in metadata passed from Django, which
can lead to security issues. Refer to the bug for more details.

Co-Authored-By: Szymon Wroblewski <szymon.wroblewski@intel.com>
Change-Id: I4821eacb0bb274befab7995f3a8f87c82d3997f5
Closes-bug: #1449260

A 'cosmetic note', so, feel free to ignore it if it's obvious:

Maybe, adding a little note of _what_ the 'relative' flag does in the commit message would be useful? Something like:

  When blockCommit or blockRebase operations are done,
  the  'relative' flag keeps the backing file paths 
  relative to other images."}, {'account_id': 8338, 'date': '2015-03-30 14:05:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 4523, 'date': '2015-03-30 14:48:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Something seems to not add up here.  Prior to the introduction of this flag, this operation would work as expected and use relative paths.  Why do we need to fail when the flag is not present rather than just using the same arguments we used with older versions of libvirt?

This introduces a requirement for a newer libvirt that doesn't seem to really be required.

Maybe eblake can provide more detail about whether this is really needed.  Did the introduction of the relative flag change the behavior when the flag is not used?"}, {'account_id': 8338, 'date': '2015-03-30 14:59:28.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Libvirt never populated relative paths in qcow2 files until the introduction of the flag; the only way to get a relative path without libvirt's help is to pre-create the files yourself and then tell libvirt to reuse external files.  Pre-creation works for snapshot and blockcopy, but not for blockpull and blockcommit.  So the libvirt flag really is a new feature, and the only way to keep relative paths in a backing chain when doing an operation that shortens the chain; it also requires new enough qemu to be supported (so even if libvirt is new enough, an old qemu that doesn't support setting the backing name to an arbitrary string as part of commit or pull will fail).

That said, I'm not familiar enough with what you are trying to do to know if you really need to use the flag.  And if you must still support older libvirt, there is always 'qemu-img rebase -u' to rewrite the backing information of a qcow2 file when there is no qemu process actively visiting the file, as the only safe way to get a file chain back into relative references if you were unable to keep it that way with libvirt's help."}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-01 06:51:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-01 06:53:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

@Kashyap, 
   I added detailed commit message and inline code comments
which helps clarify 'relative' sufficiently. Let me know."}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-01 06:56:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@eharney,
    I made sure the old behaviour stays same for the
blockRebase case but for blockCommit file-backed disks, an
excp needs to be raised otherwise Cinder would be broken.

Pls see the detailed commit message i added.

Will also dump the debug data as a patch level comment.

thanx,
deepak'}, {'account_id': 10796, 'date': '2015-04-01 06:58:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

libvirtd version 1.2.2

stack@ubuntu:~/data/cinder/mnt/f4c6ad7e3bba4ad1195b3b538efab64a$ libvirtd --version
libvirtd (libvirt) 1.2.2

Steps: 

1) Snap chain : base <- snap1 <- snap2 (snap2: active) (NOTE: All paths during snap create are relative)

2) Deleted snap1 (this causes nova to do a block Commit op)

3) Snap chain: base <- snap2 (snap2: active)

4) Dumping snap2's backing chain, we see the nova mount abs path being used as below:

stack@ubuntu:~/data/cinder/mnt/f4c6ad7e3bba4ad1195b3b538efab64a$ qemu-img info volume-de05536f-fcec-4c42-9bbb-81806632fee9.8ccadd25-dea1-4dff-9a02-83076e748599 --backing-chain
image: volume-de05536f-fcec-4c42-9bbb-81806632fee9.8ccadd25-dea1-4dff-9a02-83076e748599
file format: qcow2
virtual size: 1.0G (1073741824 bytes)
disk size: 193K
cluster_size: 65536
backing file: /opt/stack/data/nova/mnt/f4c6ad7e3bba4ad1195b3b538efab64a/volume-de05536f-fcec-4c42-9bbb-81806632fee9
backing file format: raw
Format specific information:
    compat: 1.1
    lazy refcounts: false

image: /opt/stack/data/nova/mnt/f4c6ad7e3bba4ad1195b3b538efab64a/volume-de05536f-fcec-4c42-9bbb-81806632fee9
file format: raw
virtual size: 1.0G (1073741824 bytes)
disk size: 0


5) Go back to step 1: base <- snap1 <- snap2 (snap2: active) (NOTE: All paths during snap create are relative)
6) Deleted snap2 (this causes nova to do a block Rebase (aka pull) op)
7) Snap chain: base <- snap2 (snap2: active)
8) Dumping snap2's backing chain, we see the relative path being used as below:

stack@ubuntu:~/data/cinder/mnt/f4c6ad7e3bba4ad1195b3b538efab64a$ qemu-img info volume-36774096-9d8a-4657-9cba-219dd7dbacb3.98d00fda-9241-4974-8c40-9ff825c69c99 --backing-chain
image: volume-36774096-9d8a-4657-9cba-219dd7dbacb3.98d00fda-9241-4974-8c40-9ff825c69c99
file format: qcow2
virtual size: 1.0G (1073741824 bytes)
disk size: 193K
cluster_size: 65536
backing file: volume-36774096-9d8a-4657-9cba-219dd7dbacb3
backing file format: raw
Format specific information:
    compat: 1.1
    lazy refcounts: false

image: volume-36774096-9d8a-4657-9cba-219dd7dbacb3
file format: raw
virtual size: 1.0G (1073741824 bytes)
disk size: 0

Conclusion
    So it looks like pre-1.2.7 version of libvirt, blockRebase retained the relative path but blockCommit did not."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-04-01 07:52:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

"}, {'created': '2015-04-01 06:51:23.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: Use 'relative' flag for online snapshot's commit/rebase operations

libvirt added support for _RELATIVE flag in v1.2.7 and when available this
flag _must_ be used to ensure backing paths are maintained relative during
snapshot delete operations.

Per the experiments I did using pre-1.2.7 (v1.2.2) and post-1.2.7 (v1.2.9)
my findings are below:

pre-1.2.7 (v1.2.2) behaviour:
    backing paths are maintained relative for blockRebase but not for
blockCommit operations. Per the libvirt folks, this is not by design,
but a side effect of how/when the snap chain was created. For the Cinder-Nova
online snapshot case, its broken for sure.

post-1.2.7 (v.1.2.9) behaviour:
    Although the pre-1.2.7 behaviour is seen in this case too, per the
libvirt folks, _RELATIVE flag _must_ be used to guarantee qemu maintains
relative backing paths.

Without this patch:
    _RELATIVE flag was used only for blockCommit of a network disk and
raises excp if this flag isn't present. For file-backed disks case, Cinder
is broken as qemu can't maintain relative paths.

    For blockRebase this flag is never used, probably because blockRebase
maintained relative path (see above) even before this flag came into existence.

With this patch:
    _RELATIVE flag if available, is used for both blockCommit & blockRebase
cases for both file and network backed disks.

    If unavailable, it means we are dealing with pre-1.2.7 libvirt, and
it raises excp for blockCommit case (since we can't get relative paths and
Cinder flow is broken), but only puts out a warning message for blockRebase
case (since relative paths works even for older libvirt)

Summary:
    1) Uses _RELATIVE for blockRebase if available, for both file and network
       disks. Don't raise excp if flag isn't present, thus preserving older
       behaviour.

    2) Uses _RELATIVE for blockCommit if available, for both file and network
       disks. Raise excp if flag isn't present to ensure Cinder flow isn't
       broken (old behaviour changes here, for file backed disks only)

Change-Id: I9bda95cd4ab09aed88536d4a988d6c6579441c37
Closes-Bug: 1438027

commit_message:
libvirt: Use 'relative' flag for online snapshot's commit/rebase operations

libvirt added support for _RELATIVE flag in v1.2.7 and when available this
flag _must_ be used to ensure backing paths are maintained relative during
snapshot delete operations.

This patch uses _RELATIVE flag if available, for both blockCommit and
blockRebase cases for both file and network backed disks.

If _RELATIVE flag is unavailable, it raises excp for blockCommit case
(since we can't get relative paths and Cinder flow is broken), but only
puts out a warning message for blockRebase case (since relative paths
works even for older libvirt)

Closes-Bug: 1438027
Change-Id: I9bda95cd4ab09aed88536d4a988d6c6579441c37

messages:
[{'account_id': 13790, 'date': '2015-05-06 03:34:15.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-06 03:46:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded (check pipeline).

- gate-congress-pep8 http://logs.openstack.org/95/180395/1/check/gate-congress-pep8/9aae9c2/ : SUCCESS in 2m 34s
- gate-congress-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/95/180395/1/check/gate-congress-python27/dd571cf/ : SUCCESS in 3m 34s
- gate-congress-python34 http://logs.openstack.org/95/180395/1/check/gate-congress-python34/e9df3f9/ : FAILURE in 35s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 8878, 'date': '2015-05-12 18:22:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

In general, drivers shouldn't treat these kind of fixes in an error handling, but should have a feature which can handle each release version of API since we'll need to maintain any changes of APIs in every future release.  I mean if datasouce driver supports some release version, it is better that DataSourceDriver has a method which supports different API input and/or output and CinderDriver uses the method to support Havana Cinder API.

My comment seems to be not bug but blueprint, though..."}, {'account_id': 13790, 'date': '2015-05-13 02:24:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Thank you, Masahito. I agree this is a quick and dirty patch. But it's still a cinder v2 api response. Should we create multi data source drivers for the same major version API (Cinder V2 here)? Unfortunately it won't backport microversioning in Havana/Icehouse. So we have to use workarounds."}, {'account_id': 8215, 'date': '2015-05-15 18:39:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

It's true that we'll end up with different versions of a driver for different versions of the datasource, but it's not clear to me how many different driver versions we'll have, or how to effectively manage all those versions.  

So for now I think we want to make the drivers work on reasonably current versions of OpenStack, which means letting these kinds of workarounds in.  Once we figure out the proper way to handle API versions, we'll revisit."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-15 18:39:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting gate jobs.

commit_message:
Make sure cinder ds driver can work with Havana

Havana Cinder schema has no disabled_reason so cinder ds driver
cannot translate services table.

Change-Id: Ib0f0cb57b807758e189142193c01067397877629

[{'created': '2015-05-14 21:32:23.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: bump minimum required version to 1.2.2

We've gated on 1.2.2 with Ubuntu Trusty 14.04 since Juno and RHEL 7.1
has libvirt 1.2.8.

We assume people aren't going to be running Liberty nova-compute on RHEL
< 7 because in Kilo we dropped python 2.6 support and RHEL 6.x doesn't
have python 2.7 outside of Software Collections.

This also effectively bumps the minimum qemu version to at least 1.3.0
for live snapshot.  Based on the distro support matrix:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LibvirtDistroSupportMatrix

QEMU should be newer than 1.3.0 in anything that would also have libvirt
1.2.2.

This also removes some workaround code for older versions of libvirt.

UpgradeImpact: The minimum required version of libvirt for Nova in
               Liberty is now 1.2.2 and QEMU is assumed to be >= 1.3.0.

Change-Id: Ia257780355101b7970df4a79b9ea0007d1fbb041
"}, {'created': '2015-05-15 15:53:57.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: deprecate libvirt version usage < 0.10.2

In the 2016.1 'M' release we're going to raise the required minimum
version of libvirt to 0.10.2 so add a check in init_host such that if
the version of libvirt being used is less than 0.10.2 we log a warning
that people need to move up when going to 2016.1.

According to the libvirt version distro support matrix:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LibvirtDistroSupportMatrix

This will drop support for Debian Wheezy (if not using
Wheezy-backports), openSUSE 12.2 and Ubuntu Precise 12.04 (if not using
the cloud archive).

UpgradeImpact: The minimum required version for libvirt in the 2016.1
               'M' release will be 0.10.2.

Change-Id: Ia257780355101b7970df4a79b9ea0007d1fbb041"}]
commit_message:
libvirt: deprecate libvirt version usage < 0.10.2

In the 2016.1 'M' release we're going to raise the required minimum
version of libvirt to 0.10.2 so add a check in init_host such that if
the version of libvirt being used is less than 0.10.2 we log a warning
that people need to move up when going to 2016.1.

According to the libvirt version distro support matrix:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/LibvirtDistroSupportMatrix

This will drop support for Debian Wheezy (if not using
Wheezy-backports), openSUSE 12.2 and Ubuntu Precise 12.04 (if not using
the cloud archive).

UpgradeImpact: The minimum required version for libvirt in the 2016.1
               'M' release will be 0.10.2.

Change-Id: Ia257780355101b7970df4a79b9ea0007d1fbb041

commit_message:
LVM: Pass volume size in MiB to copy_volume() during volume migration

Currently migrate_volume() in lvm.py does not pass volume size in
MiB but passes volume size in GiB to copy_volume(). The size argument
of copy_volume() requires MiB value. As a result, if the volume size
is 1GiB, copy_volume() copies only 1MiB head of 1GiB volume to the
destination volume, and then the volume data is corrupted.
This patch fixes to pass volume size in MiB.

(cherry picked from commit a5da4c353a1df17341c1e745796e00a4ec1afd21)
Conflicts:
    cinder/tests/test_volume.py
    (Added mock for create_export.)

Closes-bug: #1454835
Change-Id: I8e06195dc3625ef07bc9858d844541e37a231b73

commit_message:
Add tempest test for reactive enforcement

In the tempest test, nova.servers.set_meta() is called once the
reactive enforcement is triggered. And since 'p(x)' from
'execute[p(x)] :- q(x)' doesn't take optional/named arguments,
nova-driver must implement a wrapper for servers.set_metta() to
convert positional args to optional args.

Change-Id: Ic92fbc02db5f1564bc7ba348ef2c718cb01d5399

commit_message:
Add Sphinx machinery and initial docs.

This commit gets the doc directory and Sphinx configuration started.

Further documentation will depend on the Sphinx files and the index.rst
file at the very least.

The dev-requirements were updated to install Sphinx, and a gating script
was added to do the building for when we move to actually do gating on
the docs. The docs gate script is currently set to treat warning as
errors.

Change-Id: I977a2e53f1b0981cbc702ac53f2198d9f6a9da9d
Implements: blueprint developer-docs

commit_message:
Remove redundant check for version of `requests`

Novaclient requirements list contains next entry:
  requests>=2.5.2

so we don't need to check that installed version of requests is greater
than '2.4.1'

Change-Id: I7d270e6d75c76bc56e21f42c683fde9284a8dfd7

commit_message:
Set the Kolla build timeout to 90 minutes

We believe the Kolla build will take between 1 and 3 hours.  We
are not certain exactly how long it will take, so we plan to
start with 90 minutes and later tune the timer to match our
average run-times + 20%.

Note our gate functional job builds about 40 docker images which
takes quite awhile.

Change-Id: Ifd052464cacbe4ce4d0584277aa729ab151d48fe

commit_message:
centos/centos7: switch to epel element

Instead of manually creating epel.repo files, make use of the epel
element, which will properly install epel-release.

Change-Id: Iea7b389bc1ade716c622fd39d5e7dcf119dcb447

commit_message:
Publish traning-guide files from master again

Reactivate the checkbuild and publishbuild targets for training-guides
so that they run everywhere.

This depends on a change to training-guides to create the needed tox
sections.

Change-Id: I659ed6b384381738c2cd9944131239b4d65928ef

commit_message:
All the work done for fuel-library packaging

1) Package fuel library into three different
packages:
RPM: fuel-library6.1
ALL: fuel-ha-utils, fuel-misc

2) Install packages onto slave nodes
implements blueprint: package-fuel-components

Change-Id: Ie759857fb94db9aa94aaeaeda2c6ab5bb159cc9e

commit_message:
Add unit tests to increase coverage of cadftype

Unit tests were added to bring test coverage of
cadftype up to 98%. Coverage was increased for
ValidatorDescriptor and CADFAbstractType.

commit_message:
ramdisk: switch from lsb_release to $DISTRO_NAME

Instead of executing `lsb_release` to know the current distro being
built, use the $DISTRO_NAME environment variable, already provided by
distribution elements.

Change-Id: I22b67afb481983cc40c198fd408ad5c7f4d68bec

We havent actually codified anywhere that distro elements need to set this, and it also isnt verified in any form. Is there a reason that we prefer it over lsb_release? Seems like lsb_release should always work where DISTRO_NAME is reliant on untested convention...'}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-05-15 16:09:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Clint brings up a good point in IRC that lsb is a heavy package on some distros so DISTRO_NAME is a better solution.

Before doing these changes then id like for us to document that this is required in the element creation docs. Something that would also be really nice is a check that this variable is being set by all our distro elements (in the past few weeks I've had to add this to a few that are missing it). I think we can use some of the new testing stuff to test for this too."}, {'account_id': 12320, 'date': '2015-05-15 16:14:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@greghaynes:
DISTRO_NAME is used all over the place, unconditionally, so having an operating-system element not exporting it would resulting in errors all over the place.

Therefore, I think it is much better to make DISTRO_NAME official for good, so there is no reason to run an executable to known an information which is already available.'}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-05-15 16:29:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Until recently the centos element did not set DISTRO_NAME, and the debian element still does not.

I agree that we should adopt this as a convention, but we have to properly do that before we can start depending on it throughout. If we start depending on conventions like this before we do so then theres really no way users can expect to maintain their own distro elements and make use of the dib elements without expecting random breakage.

So, tl;dr can we please document this and make sure all our distro elements set this before we move elements over to using it.'}, {'account_id': 12320, 'date': '2015-05-15 16:44:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@greghaynes:
> Until recently the centos element did not set DISTRO_NAME

The centos element has been introduced with 8026dda8a019abcd570e25ba3c8bedc9356718c9, which does include DISTRO_NAME.

> and the debian element still does not.

The debian element depends on debian-minimal, which does provide DISTRO_NAME. Before 23aa76dff00b04ecbb2c981afc0a3e0e04c42b64, it used to provide it on its own.

> So, [...] make sure all our distro elements set this before we move elements over to using it.

All the distro elements (operating-system) *already* provide it: centos, centos7, debian, fedora, opensuse, rhel, rhel7, ubuntu.

> So, tl;dr can we please document this

Sure, we can, but I don't see how this would block my reviews for using it more. As I already said, not having it would break really lots of things (package-installs & pkg-map, for once)."}, {'account_id': 10035, 'date': '2015-05-15 16:50:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

ah! ok. So I may be off in thinking this isn't as well of an established convention. My fear is simply about breaking backwards compat with our users... documentation is just the mechanism to try and counter that.

Seems like I was off though, so have a +A."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-15 16:50:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
rax-nova-agent: switch to $DISTRO_NAME

Check for the current distribution using $DISTRO_NAME instead of
`lsb_release`.
Also, remove the existency check, as $DISTRO_NAME is supposed to be
provided by distribution elements.

Change-Id: I2276c63e9ac43576da528a70235129800c093b3e

commit_message:
Add noop tests for files injection

1) Add test to check whether catalog contains
injection of files which actually should be
installed as packages
2) Add more fixtures with astute yamls
3) Shared examples structure refactoring
4) Remove File.exists? checks from install_ssh_keys
5) Add rspec and puppet debug options
6) Misc fixes to make rspec actually work

Change-Id: I8217594cd9f2c0f19c840c0abed37d94ff80eb75
blueprint: package-fuel-components

commit_message:
Add migration_type to Migration object

From the records that could be in the database prior to now, we can
determine their type by the flavor ids on the record. So, we do that
live-ly so that we don't need to (a) bother layers above with the potential
for a migration_type=None and (b) do the conversion in a db migration.

Note that this includes a change to the API to not show this field to
the user. It will be exposed in v2.1 in a later patch.

Related to blueprint robustify-evacuate

Change-Id: Id78c91357c892e684cfd8eeb1f000a57180865bb

[{'created': '2015-05-07 17:20:05.000000000', 'message': "objects: treat EnumField and ListOfEnumField classes as abstract

Currently, objects will directly instantiate EnumField and
ListOfEnumField classes, passing in the list of valid enum
values. This is sub-optimal as the same enum type may be
needed in several objects, and we want to ensure we're always
using the same list of valid values.

To address this, change EnumField and ListOfEnumField so that
they are treated as abstract, and sub-class them every time
a new enum is required. The existing uses of EnumField have
subclasses added for them and the VirtCPUModel class is
changed to use them.

Currently there are constants for enum values defined in various
modules such as nova.compute.arch, nova.compute.hv_type, etc
These constants could usefully be turned into attributes of
the appropriate Enum subclass. This is left as an exercise for
future changes

commit_message:
objects: introduce BaseEnumField to allow subclassing

Currently, objects will directly instantiate the EnumField
class, passing in the list of valid enum values. This is
sub-optimal as the same enum type may be needed in several
objects, and we want to ensure we're always using the same
list of valid values.

To address this, introduce a BaseEnumField class that provides
the custom __repr__() impl based on the enum values. Make the
existing EnumField subclass this, to allow for continued use
of anonymous enum fields, but discourage its use in favour of
creating named enum fields by directly subclassing BaseEnumField

Change-Id: Ic7ff7d2210a99467ab3aca3a5d330bc9cd6cd592

commit_message:
Fix the sql_pool_logging config attribute

The 'sql_pool_logging' config field is a boolean value, but it was
being treated as a text value in repositories.py, so any value
supplied to it was treated as a non-None condition which enabled
SQLAlchemy pool logging always. This CR changes this field to the
proper boolean type.

Change-Id: If2c1471d5a3b1fca4ac5033754d05b386fb0cbf5
Closes-Bug: #1455493

commit_message:
objects: add a FlexibleBoolean field type

The current Boolean field type has a strict interpretation of
truth values which matches the python language interpretation.

For data that comes from the end user though, it is more useful
to have a flexible interpretation, that accepts commonly used
strings like 'yes', 'no', 'on', 'off', etc as handled by the
oslo_utils  bool_from_string() method

Since the Boolean field is part of the ABI/API, we cannot
change its semantics, so this introduces new FlexibleBoolean
and FlexibleBooleanField classes

Change-Id: Ic5ad3779646de155988e9557a53be1ddf3f78d92

Enhance documentation

Rewrite README.rst and copy it to doc/source/index.rst to add a little
bit more content.

Generate documentation for APIs. fixture, safe_utils and test submodules
are not documented.

Fix indentation in obj_reset_changes() docstring.

Fix formatting of obj_make_list() docstring.

commit_message:
[Docs] Existing users and other fixes

* Add a tutorial step about the new existing users feature (step 3)
* Move the corresponding feature request to 'implemented' and modify it a bit
* Rename step 2 to "Rally input task format"
* Add tables of contents to the lessons
* Other fixes that make docs more precise

Change-Id: Ic800fdfa3df883f267ddcae2165f804c11699bd0

commit_message:
Bring Redhat support to acceptance tests

OpenStack Infra has jobs to run this on both Ubuntu Trusty and CentOS7.

* Add minitest to Gemfile (dependency to run beaker on centos - see
  http://projects.theforeman.org/issues/2650 for details)
* separate nodepool files to have trusty & centos7 support in OS infra
* basic_nova_spec: add case for repo configuration and support
  RH systems.

Change-Id: I745fa76b2b36b0dbada83260fedffc4ee60f9c03
Closes-bug: #1444736

commit_message:
Add os-brick to cinder requirements.txt

This patch adds the os-brick pypi library to
Cinder's requirements.txt as a precursor to the
removal of cinder/brick from the codebase.

Change-Id: Ib0c0996421af1c52fe66df5479768addc40412ad

commit_message:
Pass stack to thread in resource_signal

This is the only thread that gets started without an explicit reference to
the stack. This prevents us from using a weakref in the resource, as it
will cause the Stack's reference count to hit 0 before the thread is run.
Now we explicitly pass a reference to the stack.

Change-Id: Ie51be7b54d97ef184e401e395a7e7e3a26ce003b
Related-Bug: #1454873

I agree with change, but could you explain why do you do it only for these tests? I can found some other unittests where resource may have reference on stack.
May be you plan to fix it later or I missed something special :)'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-05-15 07:47:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Btw, I don't really want to block this change and my -1 just  a way to point on question."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2015-05-15 14:15:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Because these were the only tests that were failing :)

Basically anything where we have a helper method that returns a resource like:

  def create_a_resource(self):
      stack = utils.make_stack(...)
      resource = stack['resource_name']
      return resource

will fail with Ibf80e95e69a2f27ed29754a2e0f1125e8eed0775 because the resource no longer holds a reference to the stack, so the stack will be deleted as soon as it goes out of scope (i.e. when create_a_resource() returns) and resource.stack will be None from then on.

The fix was to assign the stack as an attribute of the test case (self) in those cases, so that it remains referenced as long as the test is running. In other cases it wasn't an issue, either because the stack was already referenced by the test case, because it was created in the test function itself (instead of a helper) and thus never goes out of scope during the test, or because the stack itself is returned from the helper and thus never goes out of scope during the test.

Ibf80e95e69a2f27ed29754a2e0f1125e8eed0775 includes asserts so that if anyone does it wrong in the future they will immediately see a (hopefully) relatively helpful error message at the exact point where they try to access the already-deleted Stack object, rather than trying to track down the cause of a later "Object of type NoneType has no attribute 'foo'"-style error.'}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2015-05-15 14:29:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2015-05-15 15:21:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2015-05-15 15:41:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

> Because these were the only tests that were failing :)

lol :)

Sorry for the delay in response. Thx for the clarification, I had same thoughts, just want to be sure, that all other cases will not move to regression. 

Also I thought, that met some tests, where were used same references, but currently gate looks green (hope it was my imagination).'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-05-15 15:41:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Retain references to stacks in all unit tests

This will allow Resources to hold weak references to Stacks (so as to avoid
circular references) without causing the Stack object to be prematurely
deleted.

Change-Id: Ia76da7bc51042fb3598ef2a660d6fbf78137a37b
Related-Bug: #1454873

commit_message:
Remove contextlib.nested from tests

With the deprecation of this method in Python2.7, the neutron hacking
check has been modified to check for this (N324). Since this check has
been upstreamed (I171fbdb89892a3d4548bf2ca52f4a7dd9ef8dccb), and the
neutron-fwaas repo uses the same hacking check, the FWaaS test cases
are now failing.
This commit does the same changes as was done in neutron to remove use
of this method.

Partial-Bug: #1428424

Change-Id: I130cf3eaeccbf6a965407c76a74f8f8fa59943a4

commit_message:
Add migration_type and hidden to Migration database model

This adds an enumeration for migration_type to the schema. It does not
do any data translation in the schema migration, and allows the column
to be nullable so that we don't have to act on existing migrations.
This means that any outstanding migrations in the database will need to
be handled lazily by the upper layers.

This also adds a flag called hidden, defaulting to False. Since we are
using this new type field to record potentially admin-initiated actions,
it is desirable to allow them to be hidden from regular users at times.
This adds that field to the database so that we can support that in the
migration APIs.

Related to blueprint robustify-evacuate

Change-Id: I133d46d146415e19f5c120dfa3e37090291b1298

commit_message:
Libvirt: Use tpool to invoke guestfs api

In inspect_capabilities() of nova/virt/disk/vfs/guestfs.py, guestfs api, which
is C-extension, will hang nova-compute process when it is invoked. This problem
will result in message queue timeout error and instance booting failure. Need
to use tpool to invoke guestfs api, in order to make nova-compute switch to
other green threads before guestfs api returns.

Change-Id: I24187ba01965fb886351b78eee605bc052a94e21
Closes-Bug: 1453666
(cherry picked from commit da9671aa7f597d3dd2cd6d09bb06998b209c962a)

commit_message:
Use correct name on el7+

On el7+ platform the correct name of messagebus service is dbus.
For idempotency of module on those platforms it is required to either
use correct names and not alises or fix service provider.

Change-Id: I824f40478e9190a24f7a7833b6d84311cdec8f25

OpenStack Infra has jobs to run this on both Ubuntu Trusty and CentOS7.

* Add minitest to Gemfile (dependency to run beaker on centos - see
  http://projects.theforeman.org/issues/2650 for details)
* separate nodepool files to have trusty & centos7 support in OS infra
* spec: add case for repo configuration and support

Closes-bug: #1444736
'}]
commit_message:
Bring Redhat support to acceptance tests

OpenStack Infra has jobs to run this on both Ubuntu Trusty and CentOS7.

* Add minitest to Gemfile (dependency to run beaker on centos - see
  http://projects.theforeman.org/issues/2650 for details)
* separate nodepool files to have trusty & centos7 support in OS infra
* spec: add case for repo configuration and support
  RH systems.

Change-Id: I9189efd25a8a6894b9b0be4da45bbdd49b487913
Closes-bug: #1444736

commit_message:
Bring Redhat support to acceptance tests

OpenStack Infra has jobs to run this on both Ubuntu Trusty and CentOS7.

* Add minitest to Gemfile (dependency to run beaker on centos - see
  http://projects.theforeman.org/issues/2650 for details)
* separate nodepool files to have trusty & centos7 support in OS infra
* basic_keystone_spec: add case for repo configuration and support
  RH systems.
* rabbitmq: install module from source
* apt: pin the module
* heat encryption key parameter: use a valid length for the key

Change-Id: If9820a65f1310fe85ff43b32468b746268c04ea0
Closes-bug: #1444736

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-14 13:27:23.000000000', 'message': 'Bring Redhat support to acceptance tests

OpenStack Infra has jobs to run this on both Ubuntu Trusty and CentOS7.

* Add minitest to Gemfile (dependency to run beaker on centos - see
  http://projects.theforeman.org/issues/2650 for details)
* separate nodepool files to have trusty & centos7 support in OS infra
* basic_keystone_spec: add case for repo configuration and support
  RH systems.
* rabbitmq: install module from source
* apt: pin the module

Change-Id: I687e6b274938d622860063cb1a2494f0e7f4635f
Closes-bug: #1444736
'}, {'created': '2015-05-14 14:35:10.000000000', 'message': "Bring Redhat support to acceptance tests

commit_message:
Bring Redhat support to acceptance tests

OpenStack Infra has jobs to run this on both Ubuntu Trusty and CentOS7.

* Add minitest to Gemfile (dependency to run beaker on centos - see
  http://projects.theforeman.org/issues/2650 for details)
* separate nodepool files to have trusty & centos7 support in OS infra
* spec: add case for repo configuration and support
  RH systems.
* rabbitmq: install module from source
* apt: pin the module
* don't try to install designate on centos (packaging not ready)

Change-Id: I687e6b274938d622860063cb1a2494f0e7f4635f
Closes-bug: #1444736

[{'created': '2015-05-13 09:46:26.000000000', 'message': 'Add url_access_checker to network checker

This change introduces new entry point for network_checker, which allows
to check if it is possible to access urls give to the command.

Usage: urlchecker check <url1> <url2> <url3> ...

It will be used to check repository connectivity from slave nodes.

Change-Id: Idc04f74ad7364dee452e9151391654f828e2342d

commit_message:
Add url_access_checker to network checker

This change introduces new entry point for network_checker, which allows
to check if it is possible to access urls give to the command.

Usage: urlchecker check <url1> <url2> <url3> ...

It will be used to check repository connectivity from slave nodes.

python-requests is added to nailgun-net-check package requirements in
both rpm spec and debian `control` file.

Change-Id: Idc04f74ad7364dee452e9151391654f828e2342d
Partial-Bug: #1439686

commit_message:
Wire in load-images

Updates devtest_overcloud.sh so that it makes use of load-images
to load images in a more flexible format via the load-images utility.
Images created with devtest_overcloud_images.sh will be loaded via
the static overcloud_disk_images.yaml file. If a custom YAML
script is provided to build images that will also be used to
load images as well.

This patch also removes the hard coded OVERCLOUD_CONTROL_ID,
OVERCLOUD_COMPUTE_ID, and OVERCLOUD_BLOCKSTORAGE_ID variables
from devtest that were used to map Glance image IDs into
heat parameters. This has been replaces by a more
flexible heat environment file which is generated
via the load-images tool.

Change-Id: I78c4c532169721674b2ea58ef37d2a4b23693fae

commit_message:
Bring Redhat support to acceptance tests

OpenStack Infra has jobs to run this on both Ubuntu Trusty and CentOS7.

* Add minitest to Gemfile (dependency to run beaker on centos - see
  http://projects.theforeman.org/issues/2650 for details)
* separate nodepool files to have trusty & centos7 support in OS infra
* spec: add case for repo configuration and support
  RH systems.
* rabbitmq: install module from source
* apt: pin the module
* don't run tests on RH, packages are not ready yet

Change-Id: I45d9cbd30c414abd7fc9f6cfc100b30430273318
Closes-bug: #1444736

commit_message:
Adjust User Guide redirects

Recent changes removed the extra enduser/adminuser directories and thus
we need to adjust URLs.

Also, remove old redirects for the User Guide that have been around
since over a year.

Since those directories were only used briefly, not adding redirects for
them.

Change-Id: Ic525e9e51ba28550055889628ddf8f66b515925b

commit_message:
Use urlaccesscheck to try to retrieve repos

Add check_url_retrieval action to net_probe.rb. It uses urlaccesscheck
from network checker to retrieve urls passed as parameter.

Add check_repositories method to dispatcher. It uses above action via
orchestrator to test given urls.

Partial-Bug: #1439686
Depends-On: Idc04f74ad7364dee452e9151391654f828e2342d

commit_message:
Filter operator LPs by state

The 'languagepack list' command should only return operator
languagepacks that are in the READY state.

Currently it returns all operator LPs. This makes LPs that are in
the ERROR or BUILDING state show up in the end users list.

Change-Id: I8074319208076ac82d8c44b4428bdcca36218ea5
Closes-bug: 1453950

commit_message:
Admin users are able to access apps belonging to other tenants.

Users with an admin role (within a tenant) are able to list and
manipulate apps belonging to other tenants.

Users should be allowed access to apps that belong to the same
tenant as the user.

We need to introduce a global admin for use by customer service,
devops and devs for troubleshooting end user apps. This follows
Heats model of using a single tenant created specifically for
accessing apps belonging to all tenants.

Change-Id: I3524f47d051dd60fe3440b17f1574811f4cd1c65
Closes-bug: 1454838

commit_message:
Fix loading things in instance_extra for old instances

If we don't have db_inst['extra'] then we can't load those things. We
should just set them to None instead of exploding.

Conflicts:
	nova/objects/instance.py

Change-Id: I2ace62158faaa0b6a7df3c32f2cb9f235d178013
Closes-Bug: #1446082
(cherry picked from commit 1bfb65d5ac8f7180edf3c4ecea09c8e15982bf27)

commit_message:
Install Guide: Fix openstack service create invocation

Fix this warning that appears with openstack version 1.0.3:
 # openstack service create --type identity   --description "OpenStack
Identity" keystone
WARNING: openstackclient.identity.v2_0.service.CreateService The
argument --type is deprecated, use service create --name <service-name>
type instead.

Note that the order is different, previously "--type TYPE NAME" and
now "--name NAME TYPE".

partially implements: blueprint installguide-kilo

Closes-Bug: #1453883
Closes-Bug: #1453891

Co-Authored-By: Christian Berendt <berendt@b1-systems.de>
Co-Authored-By: Flvio Ramalho <flaviosr@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>
Change-Id: I72f89defd7f55ce2822b5b511280f40196361f68

The script report_tempest_results.py does not allow to mark all Tempest
tests as failed without tempest-report.xml. It is not convinient. Now
report_tempest_results.py can mark Tempest tests as failed without
the report.

Change-Id: I0dc77e41a3662b4724e71ec59d0299f68a4d627b

commit_message:
Small changes in report_tempest_results.py

The script report_tempest_results.py does not allow to mark all Tempest
tests as failed without tempest-report.xml. It is not convinient. Now
report_tempest_results.py can mark Tempest tests as failed without
the report.

Change-Id: I0dc77e41a3662b4724e71ec59d0299f68a4d627b

commit_message:

7232, 7233, 7234, and 7235 per [1]

Improve unit tests of general utils

This patch add unit tests for general utils
and improve coverage. Removed extra check
in change_status_description, because it's not needed.

commit_message:
Deprecate the Direct Engine

Add deprecation warning at sahara startup and during each cluster
operation with direct engine. Also add documentation about direct engine
deprecation.

Implements blueprint: deprecate-direct-engine

Change-Id: Ic478918834d3627557b0ba43873e37d9e6ff7dc9

commit_message:
Remove hash check during image upload

There were situations, when image was upload twice automatically,
because it was updated and it's hash changed.
But since these images have the same name and some of our applications
currently rely on image name, when constructing heat template it caused
problems in heat, as it could not resolve this situation,
while deploying template, generated by Murano.

Change-Id: Ib8f86f4934b2420d3c1c7e952dcbb47bcc9ab81c
Closes-Bug: #1443936

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-05-04 21:28:50.000000000', 'message': 'Fix raise syntax for Python 3

The syntax "raise a, b, c" and "raise a, b" is invalid in Python 3.

To be compatible with Python 2 and Python 3, this change:

* Replace "raise exc[0], exc[1], exc[2]" with "six.reraise(*exc)"
* Replace "raise a, b, c" with "six.reraise(a, b, c)"
* Replace "raise a, b" with "raise a(b)"

This patch was generated by the following tool (revision 8ebd9639dbf5)
with the "raise" operation:
https://bitbucket.org/haypo/misc/src/tip/python/sixer.py

Manual changes:

* Ignore changes on comments

Blueprint nova-python3

commit_message:
Fix raise syntax for Python 3

The syntax "raise a, b, c" and "raise a, b" are invalid in Python 3.

To be compatible with Python 2 and Python 3, this change:

* Replace "raise exc[0], exc[1], exc[2]" with "six.reraise(*exc)"
* Replace "raise exc_type, exc_value, exc_tb" with
  "six.reraise(exc_type, exc_value, exc_tb)"
* Replace "raise exc, msg" with "raise exc(msg)"

This patch was generated by the sixer tool version 0.2 with the "raise"
operation:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Manual changes:

* Ignore changes on comments

Blueprint nova-python3
Change-Id: I9e75321776f7734604fb1b524684065e25510a03

commit_message:
Replace iter.next() with next(iter)

On Python 3, iterators have a __next__() method, but no next() method.
Use the builtin next() function which works on Python 2 and Python 3.

This patch was generated by the sixer tool version 0.2:
https://pypi.python.org/pypi/sixer

Manual change:

* Fix indentation
* tarfile.TarFile is not an iterator and has a next() method on Python 2
  and Python 3: revert changes in
  nova/tests/unit/virt/xenapi/image/test_utils.py and changes on
  self._tarfile in nova/virt/xenapi/image/utils.py.

Blueprint nova-python3
Change-Id: Ie691d6f236a5aeef049f0b191dd07167020443d7

commit_message:
move novncproxy_base_url to nova-compute container

...otherwise the novncproxy_base_url defaults to:

http://127.0.0.1:6080/vnc_auto.html

Turns out nova-novncproxy container does not need this setting defined.

Change-Id: I224276f541639e0c69d0a626c064e03698618df1

commit_message:
Avoid excessing logging of RetryRequest exception

Such exception indicates of error condition only if
retries are exceeded. In other cases error-level logs
pollute the log file and complicate log analysis.

Change-Id: I318867043a68a6499851631593859a0fffac6038
Closes-Bug: #1433001
(cherry picked from commit 02aeda28cf8b69f39f934a3e80cb7cae04c5fc20)

commit_message:
Link to devstack guide for appropriate serial_console instructions

devstack now has an n-sproxy service that can be enabled as you'd expect.
For those that want to test the serial console support link to the devstack
configuration guide.

Change-Id: I1c12d654db401955791a40ce192ce8bd7e52f3b6

subject: libvirt: improve logging

commit_message:
libvirt: improve logging

The patch does the following:
1. in some cases the instance name was used for logging. This is
   not unique and the admin would be unable to understand which
   instance was problematic
2. One of the log messages did not have a log hint

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I7dceb22417380e9dc2c29b065ef6ee39771e8a7d

commit_message:
Fix for Ceilometer Sahara notifications test

Increase timeout at step #2 from 60 to 300 seconds because
timeout of 60 seconds is too small for changing status
of Sahara cluster to expected statuses: "Active", "Waiting", "Error"

Change-Id: Iccc4b15f3f75ce58a80c690aa350b2f358359361
Closes-bug: #1455509

commit_message:
Update guideline doc of multiple use msg case

There was confusion in a cinder review with respect
to the case where a message is used both in a log
and in an exception:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/155894/2

This update is to clarify the guidelines to help
prevent similar confusion in the future.

Change-Id: Ia26b4d3efafb8ad13c45e982a1be7aea176417e1

commit_message:
Declare DirectPublisher exchanges with passive=True

If rabbit dies, the consumer can be disconnected before the publisher
sends, and if the consumer hasn't declared the queue, the publisher's
will send a message to an exchange that's not bound to a queue, and
the message wll be lost.  Setting passive=True will cause the
publisher to fail and retry if the consumer hasn't declared the
receiving queue yet.

Co-Authored-By: Noel Burton-Krahn <noel@burton-krahn.com>
Closes-Bug: #1338732
(cherry picked from commit 434b5c8781b36cd65b7b642d723c0502e7093795)

Conflicts:
	oslo_messaging/_drivers/common.py
	oslo_messaging/tests/test_utils.py

Change-Id: I5ba4d311b97236d3a85a9f5badff61f12b08c12d

commit_message:
rabbit: fix timeout timer when duration is None

When the duration of the timeout timer used in the rabbit driver.is
None and we want that the timer return a maximum of N secs it return None
(infinite) instead of N.

This change fixes that.

Closes-bug: #1408370

(cherry picked from commit 44132d4344902f98007e6e58ea3bee56c701b400)
Change-Id: I7f4cb3075f776c63aa7dc497173677f92b68c16d

commit_message:
libvirt: safe_decode xml for i18n logging

The xml argument passed to _create_domain can be a utf-8 encoded string
which causes a UnicodeDecodeError when it is substituted into the _LE
unicode translated message. Safely decoding the xml argument before
attempting to substitute it into the error message avoids the
UnicodeDecodeError.

Closes-Bug: #1453274
Change-Id: I4cf1836f4ca9097f7c6d98c5212a14d24111fe67

commit_message:
rabbit: more precise iterconsume timeout

The iterconsume always set the timeout of kombu to 1 second
even the requested timeout more precise or < 1 second.

This change fixes that.

Related bug: #1400268
Related bug: #1399257
Related-bug: #1338732

(cherry picked from commit 023b7f44e2ccd77a7e9ee9ee78431a4646c88f13)

Conflicts:
	oslo/messaging/_drivers/amqpdriver.py
	oslo/messaging/_drivers/impl_rabbit.py

Change-Id: I157dab80cdb4afcf9a5f26fa900f96f0696db502

commit_message:
Add directory status helper function

This patch adds is_directory_updated to fileutils, which uses a cache file and
can be used to check if a directory is updated or not.

And reset_directory_status is to remove cache file of a directory.

Related-Bug: 1437992
Change-Id: I63028b1370baf9b38ba70d48d4b99532bfeb939c

commit_message:
Fixing unauthenticated middleware role bug

We regressed a few days to where the unauthenticated middleware
context is completely broken. This patch attempts to resolve the
regression through two ways. The first is to provides a way to specify
the roles through the X-Roles header. It is assumed that a deployer
using their own middleware should be providing this header. The second
is that if the X-Roles header isn't specified then the admin role is
assumed; normally this is when using barbican in dev mode.

Change-Id: Ic19270f0381b4aec2e0c8a4ce466900bc91e1597
Closes-Bug: 1455247

commit_message:
Update fake flavor's root and ephemeral disk size

In libvirt test, instance will be created with a predefined
flavor size, however the flavor's root disk and ephemeral disk
size is inconsistent to instance's root disk and ephemeral
disk size, this lead to some confusion in code review.
This patch makes them identical.

Change-Id: I06d78b8919edbd6a8a215015889619d6e7697150

commit_message:
Fix typo in rabbit driver's reconnect() method

A typo in the rabbit driver's reconnect() method can cause the retry loop
to abort prematurely, preventing proper recovery. This patch fixes that
typo and adds a test that covers that code, which was previously (AFACIT)
unexercised by unit tests.

Change-Id: I45e65e33cfc44e0824dd6590ba442d9b292720d8

Change the behaviour of ConfigFilter.register_cli_opt to:

1. If the opt is already registered before parsing, then registering
just import it.
2. if the opt is not registered before, then raise an exception named
CliOptRegisteredError.

By adding this modification, the behaviour of
ConfigFilter.register_cli_opt looks more consistent to
ConfigOpts.register_cli_opt. The solution to the question mentioned in
Bug#1366946 should be like this:

from oslo_config import cfg
from oslo_config import cfgfilter

import sys

c = cfg.CONF
c.register_cli_opt(
    cfg.BoolOpt('myflag',
                default=False,
                help='turn on myflag',
                )
)
c(sys.argv[1:])

f = cfgfilter.ConfigFilter(c)
f.register_cli_opt(
    cfg.BoolOpt('myflag',
                default=False,
                help='turn on myflag',
                )
)

print f.myflag

Closes-Bug: #1366946

Change-Id: If06e481f579c7b986a64170754d16f7d07fb4ebd
"}]
commit_message:
ConfigFilter.register_cli_opt will import a known opt and raise exception with unknown opt

Change the behaviour of ConfigFilter.register_cli_opt to:

1. If the opt is already registered before parsing, then registering
just import it.
2. if the opt is not registered before, then raise an exception named
CliOptRegisteredError.

By adding this modification, the behaviour of
ConfigFilter.register_cli_opt looks more consistent to
ConfigOpts.register_cli_opt. The solution to the question mentioned in
Bug#1366946 should be like this:

from oslo_config import cfg
from oslo_config import cfgfilter

import sys

c = cfg.CONF
c.register_cli_opt(
    cfg.BoolOpt('myflag',
                default=False,
                help='turn on myflag',
                )
)
c(sys.argv[1:])

f = cfgfilter.ConfigFilter(c)
f.register_cli_opt(
    cfg.BoolOpt('myflag',
                default=False,
                help='turn on myflag',
                )
)

print f.myflag

Closes-Bug: #1366946

Change-Id: If06e481f579c7b986a64170754d16f7d07fb4ebd
